## PART 2 — WORLD & LORE (Souls-like, environmental only)

### 2.1 The Setting
Long ago, magic was inexhaustible — wizards drew mana as freely as breath. That age ended in an event the survivors call **the Ebbing**. Now mana must be *summoned* from what's left of the world's dwindling reserve, one card at a time, through half-remembered ritual (the Channel). The old tournament grounds where wizards once competed for glory — **the Hollow Arcanum** — still stand, empty of any audience, kept alive only by the duels still fought inside it. No one quite remembers why the duels continue. They simply do.

There is no overworld because there is nothing left outside the Arcanum worth walking through. The player moves from duel to duel the way a soul moves from bonfire to bonfire — pulled forward by the ritual itself, not by a map.

### 2.2 Environmental Storytelling (Souls-style — brief, never explained outright)
- **Bonfire equivalent — "Sigil Flames":** small motes of dead mana that flare when a duelist rests near them. Flavor line on first rest: *"The flame does not warm. It only remembers."*
- **Shop equivalent — "The Reliquary":** a wall of unclaimed gear left behind by duelists who never returned to collect it. No merchant NPC needed — just a UI framed as rifling through the reliquary itself.
- **Item flavor text:** every gear piece gets one short evocative line, Dark-Souls-style, never explaining mechanics directly. Examples:
  - *Ember Wand — "It does not cast fire. It remembers being fire."*
  - *Robe of the Unnamed Rank — "Once tournament colors. No one recalls which house."*
  - *Ring of the Ember Choir — "They sang until the flame took their voices too."*
- **Enemy naming:** enemies are never "Goblin #3" — they're remnants of the tournament's dead ranks: **"A Hollowed Challenger," "The Unseated Duelist," "Echo of the Fourth Bracket."** This implies a whole dead tournament structure without ever stating it.
- **The Boss — "The Last Arcanist":** implied (never stated) to be the tournament's final champion, still fighting because the Arcanum won't let a champion leave undefeated. Mechanically, this is the only fight in the game that draws from and masters *all four* card types at once (Sorcery, Status, Creature, Wild) — the lore and the mechanical design reinforce each other without a single line of dialogue.

### 2.3 Lore Delivery Rule
No cutscenes, no NPC dialogue, no narrator voice. All lore is optional flavor text a player can choose to read (on gear, on Sigil Flames, on enemy-defeat log lines) or skip entirely without losing any mechanical information. This is both a design pillar and a scope-saver — you never need to write or trigger a single scripted story beat.

