## PART 4 — DATA-DRIVEN DESIGN APPROACH

The whole point of building this data-driven is that balance passes (Day 6) should mean editing numbers in one table, never touching logic code.

**Recommended data tables (all as flat Odin arrays of structs, no external file parsing needed for jam scope — JSON/config loading is a nice-to-have, not a requirement):**

```odin
EnemyDef :: struct {
    name: string,          // flavor name, e.g. "A Hollowed Challenger"
    max_hp: int,
    behavior: AIBehavior,
    crit_threshold: int,   // flat d20 threshold replacing timing minigame for enemies
    attrs: Attributes,
}

enemy_table := [?]EnemyDef{
    {"A Hollowed Challenger", 18, .Random,     15, {0,0,0,0,0,0}},
    {"The Unseated Duelist",  24, .Aggressive, 16, {1,0,0,0,0,0}},
    {"Echo of the Fourth Bracket", 30, .Defensive, 14, {0,1,0,1,0,0}},
    // ... add rows, never new code, to add enemies
}

GearDef :: struct {
    name: string,
    flavor_text: string,
    attr_target: string,  // which Attributes field, matched by name at equip time
    bonus: int,
    slot: string,          // "weapon", "armor", "ring", "hat", "amulet"
}

gear_table := [?]GearDef{
    {"Ember Wand", "It does not cast fire. It remembers being fire.", "arcana", 2, "weapon"},
    {"Robe of the Unnamed Rank", "Once tournament colors. No one recalls which house.", "vitality", 3, "armor"},
    {"Ring of the Ember Choir", "They sang until the flame took their voices too.", "focus", 1, "ring"},
    // ...
}
```

**Node sequence as data too:**
```odin
NodeType :: enum { Battle, Shop, Bonfire, Boss }

run_sequence := [?]NodeType{
    .Battle, .Battle, .Bonfire, .Battle, .Shop, .Battle, .Battle, .Bonfire, .Boss,
}
```
Changing pacing for the whole game becomes editing one array literal — extremely fast to iterate on Day 5-6 balance passes.

**General Odin data-driven tips:**
- Use `#partial switch` sparingly and prefer exhaustive `switch` on your enums (Odin will warn on missing cases) — this catches bugs when you add a new `CardType` or `StatusKind` and forget to handle it somewhere.
- Keep all tunable numbers (`BASE_ZONE_WIDTH`, `MAX_FIELD_CREATURES`, `BURN_TICK_DAMAGE`, d20 thresholds) as named constants at the top of one file, not scattered magic numbers — makes Day 6 balancing a single-file scan.
- Favor plain arrays/dynamic arrays over maps where order doesn't matter for lookup speed — Odin's dynamic arrays are simple and fast enough at jam scale; don't reach for anything fancier.

