## PART 5 — SCREEN & GAME STATE ARCHITECTURE

```odin
GameScreen :: enum { Battle, Shop, Bonfire, Boss, GameOver }

GameState :: struct {
    current_screen: GameScreen,
    sequence_index: int,
    player: Combatant,
    encounter: EncounterState, // only populated during Battle/Boss
}

update :: proc(state: ^GameState) {
    switch state.current_screen {
    case .Battle, .Boss: update_battle(state)
    case .Shop:          update_shop(state)
    case .Bonfire:       update_bonfire(state)
    case .GameOver:      update_game_over(state)
    }
}

draw :: proc(state: ^GameState) {
    rl.BeginDrawing()
    defer rl.EndDrawing()
    rl.ClearBackground(PALETTE_BG)
    switch state.current_screen {
    case .Battle, .Boss: draw_battle(state)
    case .Shop:          draw_shop(state)
    case .Bonfire:       draw_bonfire(state)
    case .GameOver:      draw_game_over(state)
    }
}
```
**Tip:** resist the urge to build a generic "scene stack" or transition system. A single enum + switch is enough for 4 screens in a 6-day jam. Advance `sequence_index` and re-derive `current_screen` from `run_sequence[sequence_index]` whenever a node completes.

