## PART 7 — TUTORIAL (small, in-fiction, no dialogue)

### 7.1 Design
The tutorial is the first node in the sequence — a scripted, low-stakes duel against **"A Faded Echo"** (flavor name, 12 HP, no real threat). Instruction is delivered the way Dark Souls delivers it: brief on-screen prompts tied to the *first time* a mechanic is relevant, never a wall of text up front, and never repeated once dismissed.

### 7.2 Tutorial State Machine
```odin
TutorialStep :: enum { Intro, ShowChannel, ShowCast, ShowTiming, ShowCreature, ShowStatus, Done }

tutorial_state: TutorialStep = .Intro

maybe_show_tutorial_prompt :: proc(step: TutorialStep) {
    if tutorial_state != step do return
    switch step {
    case .Intro:
        draw_prompt("Press ENTER to begin the duel.")
    case .ShowChannel:
        draw_prompt("Press SPACE to draw on what power remains.")
    case .ShowCast:
        draw_prompt("Choose a spell. It will cost what you've drawn.")
    case .ShowTiming:
        draw_prompt("Stop the mark clean to strike true.")
    case .ShowCreature:
        draw_prompt("Some workings linger. They act on their own accord.")
    case .ShowStatus:
        draw_prompt("Some markings do not fade at once.")
    case .Done:
        // no prompt
    }
}

advance_tutorial_if_ready :: proc(event: GameplayEvent) {
    switch tutorial_state {
    case .Intro:        if event == .EncounterStarted   do tutorial_state = .ShowChannel
    case .ShowChannel:  if event == .PlayerChanneled     do tutorial_state = .ShowCast
    case .ShowCast:     if event == .PlayerCastSorcery   do tutorial_state = .ShowTiming
    case .ShowTiming:   if event == .TimingResultShown   do tutorial_state = .ShowCreature
    case .ShowCreature: if event == .PlayerSummoned      do tutorial_state = .ShowStatus
    case .ShowStatus:   if event == .PlayerCastStatus    do tutorial_state = .Done
    case .Done: // no-op
    }
}
```
**Design note:** if the player never triggers a step naturally (e.g. never draws a Creature card in their opening hand), don't force it — either skip that prompt silently after a turn-count threshold, or stack the tutorial enemy/starting hand deterministically (rig the first few draws for this one encounter only) so every player sees all six prompts in their first duel. Rigging the opening hand is far cheaper than building fallback logic — just special-case the first encounter's deck order.

### 7.3 Tutorial Encounter Data
```odin
tutorial_enemy := EnemyDef{"A Faded Echo", 12, .Random, 18, {0,0,0,0,0,0}}
tutorial_forced_player_hand := [5]Card{
    {5, .Clubs, false, .Sorcery},   // guarantees a Sorcery to demonstrate Cast + Timing
    {11, .Hearts, false, .Creature},// guarantees a Creature to demonstrate summon/stance
    {1, .Spades, false, .Status},   // guarantees a Status to demonstrate field markers
    {3, .Diamonds, false, .Sorcery},
    {7, .Clubs, false, .Sorcery},
}
```
Only the tutorial encounter uses a forced hand — every subsequent battle uses the normal shuffled shared deck.

